                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Just thought I would add my own 'Why's' (though not my 'hows', as that has been adequately covered).
<br />

<br />
1 -- It ups the dps of the group, sometimes significantly, since you are not losing dps with a monk/ranger out pulling, and you are not losing time with a mob in camp if the MT is pulling.
<br />

<br />
2 -- I typically pull with tash, so that mobs START less resistant.  Makes rooting/stunning/mezzing/nuking that much easier.  IE, an accidental three pull by me is easier to lock down than an accidental three pull by someone else, because at least one mob will have lower MR for mezz or tash, leaving only two others, one of which is engaged immediately.
<br />

<br />
3 -- Since my job as an enchanter is usually done after the first 15-20 seconds a mob is in camp (tash, slow, mez/stun when multiples), I have free time to look for the next mob or mobs.  Other classes should generally still be doing damage or medding.  The relatively low mana cost of enchanter spells makes us a good choice to be running instead of sitting.  (This changes somewhat at higher end.  Thus using tepid deeds instead of forlorn, for instance.)
<br />

<br />
4 -- I enjoy it.
<br />

<br />
edit:  5 -- I have practice.  In the end, being the 'best' puller only depends maybe 20% on what class you are.  Knowledge of mob habits, their aggro ranges, their pathing, and both your and their abilities is what makes a good puller.  I'd rather a good warrior puller pull than a bad enchanter puller, even if all the above reasons still hold true.  Like anything else, practice is required to be good~.
<br />

<br />
One 'how' note:  When I still had access to AE mezz (and even still, using WoM in ldon dungeons) I would frequently pull 4-5 at a time, run, turn and mez the bunch.  Worked real nice, and scared the crap out of my Karnor's castle groups.  Woo~</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Eleandra
<br />
<a href="http://www.scienceofwar.net" target="_blank">www.scienceofwar.net</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
